@node "bugs" "KNOWN BUGS"
@toc "Contents"
               KNOWN BUGS
               ----------

The following bugs have either been fixed, or WILL be fixed on the next
release:

  -Problems when opening on a screen smaller than 640x400
  -Initial values of some effect parameters are not initialized (user must
move slider first)
  -Crashes when closing certain windows in certain orders. (for example
closing an effect window after the main effects window has been closed)
@endnode

@node "GRUNGE" "GRUNGE      "
@toc "Contents"
               GRUNGE
               ------

Grunge implements a differentiator-type effect, which adds the first
derivative of the sample to the sample. The result is racuous, grungy
sound.

Overflow options
  The clip option clips the sample if its range exceeds 127.
  The soft clip option is adjusting the dc offset of the waveform as it
approaches the saturation region, so that the higher frequencies remain
intact. This, however, may induce further distortion to the sound.
 The AS IS option lets the 32-bit bank expand without any adjustment, and
the sample bank is clipped.
 The ADJUST option expands the 32-bit bank without any adjustment, and then
copies that to the sample using scaling, so that the sample fits its range
exactly.

PowerDrain options.
 Powerdrain is used to simulate the behaviour of a real differentiator. When
using this option, the higher the output achieved by the model
differentiator at a given moment, the less powerful it will be on the next.
The LINEARLY option specifies wether this will be done linearly or
exponentially.

This effect's depth parameter can be modulated. Try a sine/square/ramp for
interesting results.
@endnode

@node "FLANGE" "FLANGE      "
@toc "Contents"
                  FLANGE
                  ------

Flange is a normal flange effect. It is affected by the @{"OVERSAMPLING" link "OVERSAMPLING" 0} option.
It can be modulated and accepts negative values. If you use a sine wave to
modulate it, you will get a PHASOR effect.
@endnode

@node "SUSTAIN" "SUSTAIN     "
@toc "Contents"
                  SUSTAIN
                  -------

This effect tries to keep a sample amplitude within a given range. The
amplitude is specified by the GAIN slider. The speed of the effect, (how
fast it can adjust to changes in amplitude) is controlled by the adaption
slider and gadget. In case you wanted  to know, the adaption gadget actually
changes the effective value of the slider by multiplying with 1,10,100 and
1000 respectively. So, a setting of 100 on the @{i}adaption slider@{ui} while the
@{i}gadget@{ui} shows SLOW, is the same as a setting of ten with the gadget showing
MEDIUM.

High values of gain and speed cause distortion, which can be surprisingly
nice.
@endnode

@node "OVERSAMPLING" "OVERSAMPLING"
@toc "Contents"
            OVERSAMPLING
            ------------

Oversampling (sometimes called anti-aliasing) is a special process that
interpolates the samples (=points) of a waveform. This is equivalent to
increasing the sample-rate of a sample on-the-fly.

Currently, only simple linear interpolation is supported. Second order
interpolation is to be added.
@endnode

@node "MODULATE" "MODULATE"
@toc "Contents"
                     MODULATION
                     ----------

 Some of the effects can have certain parameters modulated.
 This means that the parameter's will change with time (on each processing
step)
 The values can be taken from any currently used bank.
 When used as modulators, banks are automatically looped.
 Take care, though, as negative values are not supported by all
parameters!!


 Example:

 If you create a new sine wave in Bank 1 and then use Grunge with modulation
from bank 1, the value of Grunge Depth will be taken from the contents of
bank 1 and it will be a sine wave.
 But Grunge will not accept negative values, so use the DC-offset when
creating the sine wave to ensure that the contents of bank1 are always
positive.
@endnode

@node "32-bits" "32-bits"
@toc "Contents"
                  32-bits
                  -------

The 32-bit option enables 32-bit processing for all effects. If it is not
selected, processing takes place in the format of the currently used sample.
This option might be removed in the future and the processing will always
take place in 32 bits.

               32-bit format
               -------------

For those who want to know, the 32-bit format adds 8 MSBs and 8 LSBs to a
16-bit sample and 8 MSBs and 16 LSBs to an 8-bit sample.


All formats are signed internally and are formatted as such:


The 8-bit format  (byte) uses values -128 to 127 with a precision of 1

The 16-bit format (word) uses values -128 to 127 with a precision of 1/256

The 32-bit format (longword) uses values -65536 to 65535 with a precision of
1/65536
@endnode

@node "CPD Filter" "CPD Filter "
@toc "Contents"
               CPD Frequency Filter
               --------------------

This filter acts similarly to a serially-networked induction. The big
difference is that it processes samples in both directions of time and thus
cannot be used for real-time effects. Currently, it can only be used as a
low-pass filter.
@endnode

@node "White Noise" "White Noise"
@toc "Contents"
                     White noise filter
                     ------------------

 This filter tries to remove white noise. The optimal sensitivity range is
from 65 to 99 percent. The current version only eliminates noise at the
higher frequencies, but it will be extended.
 Take care when using the filter on hi-hats and snares, as their
high-frequency components WILL be removed, since they are mostly noise.
 The filter is most effective on very noisy samples and samples taken from
vinyl. Almost-clear-sounding or loud samples will be treated very badly.
@endnode

@node "OVERDRIVE" "OVERDRIVE   "
@toc "Contents"
                  OVERDRIVE
                  ---------

 Overdrive emulates a single-transistor amplifier with no DC bias. Good on
guitar samples. (try also @{"sustain" link "SUSTAIN" 0} and @{"grunge" link "GRUNGE" 0}). If requested, I will add DC
bias and a 2 transistor amp. (an idealized version - it is just a sample
processing program, not an amp simulator!)
@endnode

@node "Contents" "Contents"
@toc "Contents"
 CHRISP V0.4 - Beta Version
 ---------------------------


 This is the first published beta version of CHRISP, a novel signal
processor (See @{"Future" link "future" 0})
 It is largely in an incomplete form and not too usable, but you can play
around with some of the implemented effects and perhaps use it for
something. What I really want though, is to get some @{"Feedback" link "feedback" 0} from all of
you who have a need for similar programs. I would also like to hear
something from anybody that is willing to @{"helpĀme" link "feedback" 0} out a bit, as I do not
have the required documentation and thus unable to implement certain
futures.



